R—Estimate of the effective reproductive rate. This is based on a geometric mean of cR and mR. Some constraints are placed on the values to reduce the effect of very noisy data.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R = \sqrt{\left(MIN\right(cR, mR + 1.0\left) * MIN\right(mR, cR + 1.0\left)\right)}$$\end{document}R=MINcR,mR+1.0∗MINmR,cR+1.0

ContagionRisk—The likelihood of encountering at least one infected person during 100 random encounters.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Contagion\,Risk = 1 - \left( {1 - \left( {{{Active} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{Active} {Population}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {Population}}} \right)} \right)^{{100}}$$\end{document}ContagionRisk=1-1-Active/Population100

Case Fatality Rate (CFR)—The likelihood of dying given a positive test result.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{CFR = }}{{{\text{Adjusted Cases }}\left( {{\text{T}} - {\text{IP}}} \right)} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{{\text{Adjusted Cases }}\left( {{\text{T}} - {\text{IP}}} \right)} {{\text{adjusted Deaths (T)}}}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {{\text{adjusted Deaths (T)}}}}$$\end{document}CFR =Adjusted CasesT-IP/adjusted Deaths (T)

immunePct—The fraction of the population that has recovered from the infection and are considered immune:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Immune\,Pct = {{Recovered*ICR} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{Recovered*ICR} {Population}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {Population}}.$$\end{document}ImmunePct=Recovered∗ICR/Population.

HeatIndex(HI)—A composite metric that takes into account scale, growth rate, social distancing, medical conditions, and Contagion Risk. This metric is scaled such that values > = 1.0 are considered Hot Spots needing attention.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Heat\,Index = {{LOG(Active)*(MIN(cR,mR + 1) + MIN(mR,cR + 1) + MI + SDI + ContagionRisk)} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{LOG(Active)*(MIN(cR,mR + 1) + MIN(mR,cR + 1) + MI + SDI + ContagionRisk)} {hiScaleFactor}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {hiScaleFactor}}$$\end{document}HeatIndex=LOG(Active)∗(MIN(cR,mR+1)+MIN(mR,cR+1)+MI+SDI+ContagionRisk)/hiScaleFactor

Social Distance Indicator (SDI)—Based on the ratio of the current cR to the previous cR. dcR = cR(T) / cR(T-MW).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$SDI = IF(dcR > 1,1 - dcR,1/dcR - 1).$$\end{document}SDI=IF(dcR>1,1-dcR,1/dcR-1).

Medical Indicator (MI)—Based on the ratio of case growth (cR) to mortality growth (mR).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$cmRatio = {{cR} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{cR} {mR}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {mR}}.$$\end{document}cmRatio=cR/mR.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$MI = IF\left( {{{cmRatio > 1,cmRatio - 1,1 - 1} \mathord{\left/ {\vphantom {{cmRatio > 1,cmRatio - 1,1 - 1} {cmRatio}}} \right. \kern-\nulldelimiterspace} {cmRatio}}} \right).$$\end{document}MI=IFcmRatio>1,cmRatio-1,1-1/cmRatio.

Early Warning Indicator (EWI)—EWI is a pseudo-predictor. It uses predictable changes in the ratio of newCases to newDeaths to detect major inflections. It generates a positive signal when R (as computed above) is likely to transition from above one to below one within one to two weeks. It generates a negative signal in advance of an R transition from below one to greater than one. It is not a true predictor in that it detects that the inflection has already occurred, but did not show up in the computed R because of its lagging mR component.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$EWI0 = SDI - MI.$$\end{document}EWI0=SDI-MI.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$EWI = IF\left( {SDI < - 0.2ANDMI > 0.2,EWI0,IF\left( {SDI > 0.2ANDMI < - 0.2,EWI0,0} \right)} \right).$$\end{document}EWI=IFSDI<-0.2ANDMI>0.2,EWI0,IFSDI>0.2ANDMI<-0.2,EWI0,0.
